SHIEL v. MILLER. (Supreme Court, Appellate Term. December 11, 1906.) Appeal—Record—Insufficiency. Where the notice of appeal recites that an appeal is taken from a judgment of dismissal, and the record does not contain such judgment, the case will be remitted to the trial court for such action as the parties may deem proper. [Ed. Note.—For cases in point, see Cent. Dig. vol. 3, Appeal and Error, §§ 2830-2832.] Appeal from Municipal Court, Borough of Manhattan, Thirteenth District. Action by John J. Shiel against John L. Miller. From a judgment for defendant, plaintiff appeals. Case remitted to trial court.

Argued before GILDERSLEEVE, FITZGERALD, and DAVIS, JJ.

A. D. Pape, for appellant. J. L. Miller, for respondent. *790PER CURIAM.

According to the notice of appeal herein, the plaintiff appeals from a judgment dismissing his complaint. The record on appeal does not contain any judgment dismissing the complaint.

Case sent back for such further action as the parties deem proper to take.
